@mcneazy for pristine pop, edit the fuck outta them drums, get them gridded and feeling great. 9 times outta ten gridding them will actually improve the feel, and in the spots where it doesn’t you can always comp back in. 
Then edit bass to the kick & snare, when it’s right the bottom will tell you. 
Then call Beckley to edit your vocals.

@Skyler Young what Noah said. Song/ singer dependent. Usually a combo of both. 

Another dimension to think about is processing. What you hear in an unmixed vocal is different than mixed. If a vocal gets compressed and brightened in the mix, new things pop out. I try to process as close to what I think the final vocal will sound like before I comp.

Discord-related anecdote: I had a song mastered by @Nomograph Mastering last week where when I got the master back, I heard a few clicks in the vocal that needed adjusting. Ruairi made my mix clearer and it revealed a couple things I missed in my vocal comp.

@LAPhill was thinking of you today while doing some “scoring” for my wedding video (DIY slideshow / iPhone video montage.) 

I loaded up Keyscape cinematic grand, Spitfire BBC Orch on 4 tracks, (violins, violas, cellos, horns,) and went at like I would a vocal arrangement- one voice at a time, which was great for internal voice leading and lead to some beautiful & unexpected chords. 

Came together really fast too.

@Matthew The Cooke🎄🎅🏻 @cian riordan - I decided to add one more thing to hopefully clear this up. 

Focusing on vocal panning, I  have the music go down while the lead performs what’s about to be panned around with the intention of having it be easier to perceive after it’s panned and buried, proactively trying to train the listeners ear to understand the BGs in the section that follows without them having to focus their mental energy there, since the bridge before gave their brain enough dots to connect what’s being said on the sides while still able to focus on the middle.

That’s my intention at least, and I liked the outcome, and at the very least I hope me bringing this up spurs more thoughts around panning.

