@cian riordan 

Extreeeemly subtle point I'm about to make....

I find that when I'm lengthening or shortening a note (usually a vocal where the waveform varies across a short bit of note), occasionally a zero crossing is not as phase accurate as lining up the largest/ most dominant part of the waveform. So I'm always editing for waveform coherence. It's rare that it makes a difference but it's happened enough times I don't do fade-less zero crossing anymore.

@peterlabberton @Zack Hames 

today was a tough one. I finished the arrangement yesterday, got the vocals in at 7:30pm today. I had to tune and mix to get it done by 11pm today because of the time zones. These suggestions would have worked with a bit more time, I should have phrased the post differently. I said it’s not the lack of time, but clearly it was 😥

Looking back, I could have used a quick walk- but i felt like I wouldn’t be able to finish it even if I took no breaks. I ended up turning it in without background vocals because i didn’t get to tune them

@Beck Nebel I'm doing the same thing as Matt B. The techniques just broaden as one tries to reallllly lengthen a note.

This often happens when I'm doing a writing session and we do 30 mins of scrambling to record vocals at the end. I always get a lead where I realize after fact that a word should have been held out to match another word, or a part was sung out that should have been more staccato. 

And then I have to deliver an A+ sounding finished record (fuck a "demo"). So I use my whole bag of tricks to reallllly lengthen some shit. Many tools and tricks to use, and I can rarely be certain what will work best before I try them.
